Got it. No proxy config in the image at all — correct approach for an air-gapped LAN where everything is internal. Gradle should connect directly to Artifactory without any proxy involvement.

The only thing that matters then is: **make sure no proxy ends up in the image**. Since you're building `FROM ubi9/openjdk-21:1.24-2.1778501191` fresh (not from the broken v9), the bad `/opt/gradle/gradle.properties` from v9 won't be inherited. You just need to ensure the extracted Gradle zip also doesn't bring one in.

## Check the zip first

```bash
cd ~/Gradle_8.9
unzip -l gradle-8.9-bin.zip | grep "gradle.properties"
```

If that shows any `gradle.properties` inside the zip, check its contents:
```bash
unzip -p gradle-8.9-bin.zip "*/gradle.properties" 2>/dev/null | cat
```

The official Gradle 8.9 binary zip does **not** include a `gradle.properties` — so you should get nothing. That means after `COPY gradle-8.9/`, there will be no proxy config at all. Good.

## Extract the zip

```bash
cd ~/Gradle_8.9
unzip -q gradle-8.9-bin.zip
ls -d gradle-*/
# Should show: gradle-8.9/
```

## Fix the ARG version mismatch

Your Dockerfile has `ARG GRADLE_VERSION=8.9.0` but the zip extracts to `gradle-8.9/` (not `gradle-8.9.0/`). That's the only change needed to the Dockerfile:

```dockerfile
FROM artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/itepaypg-sbiepay2-docker-virtual/ubi9/openjdk-21:1.24-2.1778501191
LABEL maintainer="devops.sbiepay@sbi.co.in" \
      image.name="epay-build-java-gradle" \
      image.version="1.0.0" \
      image.gradle.version="8.9" \
      image.description="Java CI build: OPENJDK 21 + Gradle 8.9" \
      image.base="ubi9/openjdk-21:1.24-2.1778501191"

ARG GRADLE_VERSION=8.9
ENV GRADLE_HOME=/opt/gradle \
    PATH=/opt/gradle/bin:$PATH

COPY gradle-${GRADLE_VERSION}/ /opt/gradle/
RUN chmod -R a+rX /opt/gradle

WORKDIR /workspace
USER 1001
```

## Build, verify no proxy, push

```bash
cd ~/Gradle_8.9

# Build
podman build -t artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/itepaypg-sbiepay2-docker-local/custom-ci/gradle-8.9-jdk-21:v10 .

# Verify: no proxy anywhere in the image
podman run --rm \
  artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/itepaypg-sbiepay2-docker-local/custom-ci/gradle-8.9-jdk-21:v10 \
  bash -lc '
    echo "=== gradle version ==="; gradle --version | grep Gradle
    echo "=== java version ==="; java -version
    echo "=== proxy check in gradle dir ==="
    find /opt/gradle -name "gradle.properties" | xargs cat 2>/dev/null || echo "NO gradle.properties found — GOOD"
    echo "=== proxy env check ==="
    env | grep -i proxy || echo "NO proxy env vars — GOOD"
  '

# Push
podman login artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443
podman push artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/itepaypg-sbiepay2-docker-local/custom-ci/gradle-8.9-jdk-21:v10
```

Expected output from the verify step:
```
=== proxy check in gradle dir ===
NO gradle.properties found — GOOD
=== proxy env check ===
NO proxy env vars — GOOD
```

That's the clean state. No proxy in the image means Gradle resolves Artifactory directly, exactly as your `settings.gradle`/init script intends.

## Then update the pipeline and run

Bump the image in `base-setup.java.gradle.yml` to `:v10` and trigger the pipeline. The `update-ca-trust` step in your `before_script` handles TLS trust at runtime as before — nothing changes there.
